{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689895/1957102701/0588.xml":{"full_text":"Page 6\nTHf KIY WEST CITIZEN Sunday, OeUbar 1957\nThe Key W est Citizen\nPublished Sunday Morning and Every Week Day Afternoon,\nExcept Saturday\nNORMAN P. ARTMAN Editor Publisher\nMARGARET FuKESMAN City Editor\nCUT RTLEY AdvartininK Manager\nRAYFORD ROBERTS Circulation Manager\nPERCY CLRRY Mechanical Superintendent\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nEntered at Key West, Florida aa\nSecond Class Matter\nCARRIER SUBSCRIPTION RATES\n1 T.\u00bbr |IS SO\nMonths -7 \u00abA\n1 Month 1\n1 Week 30\nMAIT. RATES\n1 Year IJ SA*\nMontha so\nI Mentha 4so\nI Month i~ 5\n(No weekly mail subscriptions Accepted)\nNATIONAL ADV E RTISIN G REP R ES ENT AT IV ES:\nTHEIS* SIMPSON CO, INC\n1 E. 54th St New York 22, N T.\nBranch Offices in Principal Cities\nBusiness Outlook\nExcellent For Key West\nAn we at The Citizen give our readers our first\nSunday newspaper, we\u2019re pretty optimistic about the\nlong-term future of our town.\nWe think we\u2019ve got reason to be. We\u2019ve been\nlooking at the record. And the record shows a steady\ngrowth, over the past few years, in business here: in\nthe number of new electric meters, in the money Key\nWesters have put in savings accounts, in the retail sales\ntotals and in the U. S. Navy\u2019s investment here.\nThis year looks like a good one, we think\u2014and\nhere\u2019s why we think so:\nIn 1956, \u201cconsumer business\u2019\u2019 in Key West \u2014the\nmoney spent in stores, repair shops and business places\n\u2014hit an all-time record of $38,455,000, more than 38\nper cent above what it was two years before. And the\nU. S. Census of Business report, which gives those fig\nures, tells us the average gain, over the United States,\nwas just 13 per cent.\nWe just received a report from the U. S. Depart\nment of Labor\u2014it's in our business section today\u2014that\nin 1956, with a nation-wide drop in home building. Key\nWest stood up better than most towns. We built 171\nnew dwellings that year, 11 per cent less than the year\nbefore. The average drop? It was 18 per cent.\nRight now, plans are cooking to build more apart\nments, here in town, for Navy families. Several busi\nness interests are planning new buildings, too. And how\nmuch is building, this fall, running below last fall\u2019s\nlevel? Not much, judging by the building permits is\nsued by the City of Key West.\nPermits for $370,282 worth of construction were\nissued last month\u2014September. 1957.\nThat\u2019s about $36,000 less than the $406,960 figure\nfor September, 1956.\nMeanwhile, every other \u201cbusiness indicator\u201d\nshowed that Key West has grown, not declined, since\nlast September.\nThe savings and loan company\u2019s assets went from\n$2,238,698 in September. 1956 to $2,696,126 last month\n\u2014a 24 per cent rise. We sold more gasoline: the city\nelectric system gained 338 new customers; 574 new\ntelephones were installed in Key West and 278 new\nwater meters went in within the city limits. Much more\nelectricity was used, too.\nHow about the Navy\u2019s future here?\nIt looks pretty solid, to us.\nAt a meeting a few days ago, we heard definite,\ndetailed figures on the amount of money that the U- S.\nNavy has invested in Key West, and the amount it pays\nto ita officers, enlisted men, dependents and civilian\nworkers here every year. The figures were staggering.\nThe Naval Base commander reported the govern\nment has a total investment in land, buildings and equip\nment on shore and in ships, planes and other craft based\nhere nf $741,000,000. The annual payroll? For Navy\nmen, dependents and civilian workers, it's roughly\n$32,250,000 a year.\nWith anti-submarine warfare taking on an ever\nmore important aspect as Russia goes all-out on her sub\nmarine building program, the future of the Navy, in\nKey West, looks solid as our own \u201cRock\u201d from here.\nFor all these reasons\u2014and many more\u2014we simply\ncan't join the prophets of doom and gloom. We\u2019re\nlooking for a good winter season, and a good future\nbeyond.\nCrossword Puzzle\n29 Mongrel\n30 Springs\n31. Couch\n32 Burrowed\n33. Lift\n34. Dude\n35 Reigning\nbeauty\n36 Glossy\nfabric\n39. Firearm*\n41. Change the\norder of\n43. English\nletter\n44. Ugly\nmonster\n45. Press\n46. Employ\n47. Body of\nwater\n48. Canvas\nshelter t\n49. Worm\nACKOSS\n1. Serpent\n4. Shape\nWithered\n12. Pronoun\n13. Bowfin\n14. Conceited\nperson\n15. Cop.'\n16 Contribut\ning\n11. Sewing\nloosely\n20. Parts of a\nchain\n21. Destroys\n22. Sharp\nprojection\n23. City in\nFlorida\n24. Squeeze\n25. C. Amer,\ntree\n21. Sweetsop\nMA;NiGMG|L| I I IT\nAiG*A PMI a ci.RATE\nT| 1 |T OMa G|EMojx|EiN\n5 TjU PIMDMBOIvie- R T\nA T EWt RAC ERHpO\nL E s smo'p e\u00dfs t o w\na'dJl ate s Tj|o n e\n\u25a0|B D E .sM a E R OHI\ns H A o R A.NtC-Hl\nE A 5 EMU L e\u00dfg A LE\nORE Si DE SME D\u2018\u00a3 N\ni T EjPU^.O.O r BROS^S\nSolution of Saturday's Puaxlt\n8. Twig\n9 Emerald\nIsle\n10. Skating\narena\n11. Poultry\nproducts\n17. Biblical\ncountry\n19. Points\n22. Shake\n23. Flap\n24. Flagon\n25. Short\nconcluding\nspeech\n26. Groundless\n27. Full of:\nsuffix\n29. Drinking\nvessel\n30. Condiment\n32. Puts on\n33. Take\noffense at\n34. Inflirted a\npenalty\n35 Buffalo\n36 Halt\n37. Constella\ntion\n38 Mountain\nlake\n39. Minute\norifice\n40. Perceives\n42. Fruit Jtona\nDOWN\n1. King of\nIsrael\n2. Part\n3. Taken for\ngranted\n4. Cereal\n5. Signs\n6. Circlet\n7. Rabid\nHALLOWFEN CAME EARLY THIS YEAR! 1\n1 JO\nw\n'O\nPEOPLE\u2019S FORUM\nThe Citizen welcome* expre\u00bb\u00bbion\u00ab of the view* of Ws reed\ner\u00ab, but the editor reserves the right to delete any items which\nare considered libelous or unwarranted. The writers should be\nfair and confine the letters to 200 words and write on one side\nof the paper only. Signature of the writer must accompany the\nletters and will be published unless requested otherwise.\nEditor, Th? Citizen:\nTo The Citizens of Momoe County,\nAs a fellow citizen, property own\ner and taxpayer of Monroe Coun\nty I wish to sec Monroe County\ngrow and prosper. In order to\ngrow and prosper we cannot be\nthrottled by large taxes. We are\nall conscious of the fact that tax\nes have risen each year and be\nlieve it is time we do something\nto reverse this trend and make\nthe government work for the peo\nple instead of the people work\nfor the government.\nThe point I am taking issue on\nis the proposed tax increase\nfor the mosquito control district\nLet us draw the line on this one.\nAsk yourself the following ques\ntions:\n1. How long wi.l the district\nneed the increased funds?\n2. What provisions are made to\nreduce or eliminate this tax when\nthere is no longer a need for it?\n3. What provisions are being\nmade to prevent any of this money\nbeing diverted to other uses?\n4. What provision is made to\nreturn any surplus to the property\nowners of Monroe County instead\nof the State Treasury?\nI am for this increase provided\nthe four questions are answered in\nfavor of the taxpayer. I believe\nthat it is a good idea to let ali\nthe taxpayers vote on this issue\nbecause any increase in tax is\nusually passed on to the tenants,\nthere by giving everyone an in\nterest in the tax increase.\nMy answers to the four ques\ntions may give you some ideas\nto pass on to our esteemed Sen\nator and Representative who ini\ntiated this bill.\n1. I believe that Mr. Warner\nwill give us a fair idea of how\nlong he will need this increase un\nder todays circumstances. But\nthe Keys are growing and a'\nthey build up and breeding\nplaces are stamped out the need\nwill diminish from year to year\n2. There should be a time limit\nof 10 years set on the bill with\nprovisions for a five year exten\nsion to be made only upon the\nvole of the public at General Elec\ntions. The millage rate should be\nadjusted each year as the needs\nof the district dimish.\n3. and 4. These two can he\nanswered together. Specify in the\nhill that all money will go to\nthe district and that any surplus\n\"SWELL PEOPLE\"\nEditor, The Citizen:\nI would like to thank the sail\nor who found our baby on ths\nstreet at 6 a. m. Friday; also\nthe help of the woman with the\ncops who brought him home.\nWe didn't realize that our son.\nage I 1 a years, could get up so\nearly and leave the house but\nwe sure know now and will use\nanother lock on the door.\nA person sure does appreciate\nthe cops at a time like this, in\nrfaet, can t imagine what we would\ndo without such swell people as\ncops.\nMrs. L. J. Muse\n101-D Peary Court\nBiochemist Dies\nST. LOUIS. Oct. 26 IP Dr.\nGerty Theresa Cori. 61. biochem\nist who shared a 1947 Nobel Prize\nwith her husband. Dr. Carl Con.\nJ died today from a rare bone dis\nease.\nPhysicians said cause of death\nwas complications from mye.ofi\nbrosis, a bone marrow disease.\nShe had been ill with the disease\nfor many years.\nDr. Con and her husband shared\nthe 1947 Nobel Prize for their\nstudies on the body\u2019s uses of\nstarches and sugars.\nShe had been professor of bio\nlogical chemistry a: the Washing\nton University school of medicine\nhere since 1947\nThe t on* shared their Nobel\nPrize with Dr. R. A. Houssay of\nBuenos Aires\nI Houston. Tex., has very \"spe\ncial\" traffic regulations for pe\ndestrians because it has tery\nwide streets. A jaywalker caught\n.in the middle of those wide streets\nl is in plenty trouble.\nON TAX INCREASE\nwill he taken into account when\nfiguring next years tax.\nLet us write to Representative\nPapy and Senator Neblett and ex\npress our desire to put some re\nstrictions on this tax increase.\nIn the future we should make\nsure that our legislators will put\na lime limit on all tax bills and\nthat no tax bill can be extended\nwithout the consent of the public\nat General Election.\nW. H. WOODWARD.ADC\nPolitical\nAnnouncements\nMUNICIPAL ELECTION,\nNOVEMBER 5, 1957\nFor Mayor\n(GROUP 1)\nLUIGI CELLUCCI\nFor Mayor\n(GROUP 1)\nDR. DELIO COBO\nFor Mayor\n(GROUP 1)\nC. B. HARVEY\n(Re-Elect)\nFor City Commissioner\nBILL G. CHAPPELL\n(ReElect)\n(GROUP 2)\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 2)\nHARRY F. KNIGHT\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nLOUIS CARBONELL\n(Re-Elect)\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nJACK E. CLARKE\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nLOUIS M. J. EISNER\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nARTHUR MULBERG\n\nbor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 3)\nJ. R. \u2018Cowboy\u2019 W ATSON\nlor Litv Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nJACK C. DELANEY\n(Re-Elect)\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nCHARLES PARRA\nFor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nAUSTIN ROBERTS\nFor Lity Commissioner\n(GROUP 4)\nPAUL J. SHER\n\nFor City (Commissioner\n(GROUP 5)\nJOE FERNANDEZ\n(Re-Elect)\ntor City Commissioner\n(GROUP 5)\nJAMES A. (Jim)\nI FLENNER I\nKey West\nIp Days Gone By\nOct. 27, 1937\nA mentally ill crew member of\na tanker jumped overboard while\nthe ship was about four miles\neast of American Shoals light.\nAt the time, a Coast Guard boat\nwas enroute to the tanker to bring\nthe man ashore. A search of the\narea revealed no trace of the body.\nThe SS Tiger of the Standard\nOil Co. is due here tomorrow to\ntake on fuel oil. The ship is en\nroute from Dakar. Africa.\nV. S. Senator C. O. Andrews\nwill be here next weekend. He\nwill inspect parts of the Over\nseas Highway.\nThe Key West High School and\nGlee Club will present a music\nhour Sunday at 4 p. m. in the\nhigh school auditorium.\nOct. 27, 1947\nCommissioner Albert Cooper\nand two members of the Key West\nHousing Authority, Joseph Cates\nand Ralph Bethancourt. 'left for\nMiami this morning. They will\nattend a meeting of the Congres\nsional Committee on Housing to\npresent data on low rent hous\ning.\n\nJohn Sandborn, Stale Road De.\npartment photographer, was here\ntoday, making motion pictures of\nKey West and the vicinity. The\nfilms will be shown in public\nschools throughout the state.\nAn ordinance governing charter\nboats passed the city council on\nfinal reading. It requires opera\ntors of such boats to take an ex\namination and sets residence re\nquirements at one year in the\nstate and six months in Key West\nI lie Irish Gels \u2019Em\nMILWAUKEE fAP) Michael\nPeter Murray, Jr., 27, says an\nIrishman enjoys certain social\nand business advantages that\nothers don't.\nSo he filed a petition in Cir\ncuit Court asking that his name\nbe changed to Michael Patrick\nMurray, Jr.\nThe Santo Tonias hospital in Pa\nnama is supported by a national\nlottery.\nCITIZEN RADIO LISTINGS\nWKWF RADIO\n\u2022UNDAY MORNING\ng 00 Forerest i 10.00 Healing*\nns News 10.30 Bible Class*\ng 15 Hymn Time 11 no Frank Ernest*\nIi no Glad Tidings 11:15 Music\n9:15 Christophers ill 45 Forecast\n9:30 Propnecy* I 11:30 News\n\u2022UNDAT AFTERNOON\n12:00 Cunningham I 3:30 News*\n12:15 Melodie. 3 35 Melodies*\n12 45 Chr. Science* j 5 no News*\n12 55 Warm Up* 4:05 Sports*\n1:00 Gams of Day* 4:10 Rands, Bonds*\n5:00 Musie\n\u2022UNDAT EVENING\na no Headlines* i no News*\n5:15 P Hane.'* 05 Sports*\nSWO Howe* io Music Hall*\n6 45 G. Sokol sky* 9 00 Music\n7 00 Derision* 11 M Nev\n7 30 Lutheran Hi 11 15 Music\nI 12:00 Sign Off\nWCKR RADIO\n\u2022UNDAT MORNING\ng on News 9 45 Musie\nR 15 Art of Living 1 10:00 News\nr in church Sen. in 05 Monitor\no no News i 11 00 News\n9ns NaCl Pulpit \u0964ll ns Monitor\n9:30 Golden Yrs 11.30 Melody Hour\n\u2022UNDAT AFTERNOON\n12.00 News 3 05 Monitor\n12-15 Melody Hour 400 News\n100 News 4 05 Monitor\n1 05 Monitor 5:00 News\n130 I. Weik 50 3 Mon Take 15\n2.00 News 5 30 Editor\n205 Monitor 5 45 News\n3:00 News\n\u2022UNDAT EVENING\n5 on Drew Pearson \u20193O Smith\na 15 B Considine l n on t athohe Hr.\ns 30 Monitor 10:30 Monitor\n00 New s 11:00 Newi\n7 05 Monitor 11:05 Memory Tim.\nmondat morning\nt^^L opener\n6 06 Frohe Vewt\"'\u2019 Wr d\n^^iie B,y\non News 10 30 Bandstand\n1 11 no News\n7?5 Rambler II Bandstand\ng no Frolic\nWQAM Radio\n\u2022UNDAT MORNING\n1.00 Music Thru \u00bb30 Social Secur\n\u2022SS^Newa 1111 9 45 Golden Yeara\n0:00 Fla. stat.\n5 >5 News Employment\n7 00 Musie 0:15 Rescue M a-\n7 St NtWf StOH\n1.00 Broadway In 0:30 Hemew\nReview Scripture\ng 15 Hour of St. 0 55 News\nFrancis ion Teenagers\ng 30 Vote Of Speak\nPrnpher- .11 Cm at Gablet\n9 no Radio BiM. Methodise\nClaes\nWKWF\n1600\nON YOUR DIAL\nJesse Montgomery Is Awarded\n33rd Degree In Scottish Rite\nc\nAdvices have been recieved in\nKey West to the effect that Jesse\nJ. Montgomery has been award\ned the 33rd degree of Scottish\nRite Masonry by the Supreme\nCouncil of Scottish Rite at Wash\nington, D. C., within the past\nfew days. This is the highest de\ngree which can be awarded in\nthe world.\nMany years ago it wa\u00ab neces\nsary to travel to Scotland to ob\ntain this degree when so selected\nand it has only been within recent\nyears that it is being awarded in\nthis country.\nJ. J. Montgomery is a native of\nAthens, Ala., and served sixteen\nyears in the Navy. Following that\nservice he was selected for civil\nservice and is presently serving\nas shipping and receiving super\nvisor in the Navy Yard here.\nHe was raised a Master Mason\non March 15. 1946, and made\nMaster of Anchor Lodge F. A. M.\nNo. 182 in 1953; received the 32nd\ndegree in Scottish Rile on Maren\nKnight Commander of the Court\nof Honor in October 1951.\nHe has served as Master of all\nScottish Rile Bodies in Key West;\nis presently a member of Mahi\nTemple of tbe Shrine, a past pre\nsident of the Key West Shrine\nClub and a past Ambassador of\nMahi Temple.\nHe holds honorary memberships\nin Dade Lodge No. 14. Felix Va\nrella Lodge No. 64 and Marathon\nLodge No. 323 F. A M. Pre\nsently m Scottish Rite masonry\nhe performs work in the 6tn.\n14th. 18th and 21st degrees and\ncommunicates many others.\nHe worked for two years or\nganizing a Masonic temple at Ma\nrathon and during the past year\nwas instrumental in the charter\ning of Marathon Ix>dge No. 323\nf A M. He is an Advisory in\nthe Robert J. Perry Chapter of\nOrder of DeMolay and has re\nceived the Legion of Honor de\nsignation in this body.\nOther prominent Masons in the\ncommunity who have been award\ned the 33rd degree are Horace\nO Bryant, Ross Sawyer, Gerald\nH. Adams and Marcel\u2019 A. Ma\nzeau.\nAt the same ceremonies in\nWashington John C. Adams has\nbeen selected as Knight Com\nmander of the Court of Honor\nIn 1948 he was Worthy Patron\nof the Order of Eastern Star in\nKey West. He received his Scot\ntish Rite degrees in 1944 having\nreceived the 32nd degree on May\n24th of that year.\nKey West 1600\nMONDAT MORNING\n5 no F.srly News I g 05 News\n6:05 Mus Clock g;l5 Mus. Clock\n7:00 News 9:00 Breakfast Cl\n7:05 Mus. Clock 10:00 Morning Med\n:30 Treas Chest 1015 Woman s Wid\n7:45 Forecast 10:30 Girl Marries*\n7:50 Baseball Rnp 10:4.5 Whisp Sts\n7:55 News 11:00 True Story*\ng: 00 World News 1 11:30 News\n11:35 Bandstand\nMONDAT AFTERNOON\n12:00 Harvey 3:30 News*\n12:15 Bi Ow nlie 3:35 Melodies*\n12:30 Forecast 4:00 Mus. Corner\n12:35 News 5:00 Melodies*\n12:45 Music 5:30 News-\n12:55 Warm Up* 5 35 Melodies\n1:00 Game of Day* 5:45 Sports\n\u2022Denotes Network\nWKWF\n1600\nON YOUR DIAL\nMiami 610\nMONDAT AFTERNOON\nno New. I 3 no New.\n12 05 Lunch Musie 3ns Matin*.\n12:45 Weather 3:30 Woman HOU**\n12 50 Top Tune 3:45 Pepper Young\n12 55 Tell Me. Dr. 4on News\nJ 00 New a j 4:05 Frolic\n1.05 Matinee 5 no News\n2 00 News 1 5 05 Frolic\n2:05 Confessions 5:40 Alex Dreier\n2 30 1 Man\u2019s Kam 5.45 Nevs\n2;45 Dr. Gentry\nFor Quality\nPrinting\nThe Artman Press\nCITIZEN BLDG. CY 6 5661\n\nMiami 560\n\u2022UNDAT AFIERNOON\n12:00 Platter Poll 3:55 News\n12:55 News 3:00 Gerry Spina\n1:00 Gerry Spina 3:55 News\n1:55 News 4 00 Top 40 Snow\n2 no Gerry Splnn 4:55 News\n2:55 News 9:00 Tnp 40 Show\n3.00 Gerry Spirm 5 55 Sports\nJ\nirymi FTENIMt\nno Tnp 40 Anew 9 55 News\n6:55 News 10:00 Jack Purring\n7:00 Rhylbm At ton Show\nRandom 10:55 Newt\n7:55 News 11:00 Jack Purring\n8.00 Rhvthm At ton Show\nRandom 12 no Music Thru\ng 55 News Th. Night\n9 no Rhy